Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.107 --> 00:00:07.523
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
Welcome, Google.

00:00:07.523 --> 00:00:08.490
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:10.165 --> 00:00:11.460
Thank you, guys.

00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:16.980
Born in Chicago, Illinois,
Jay Chandrasekhar

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:20.970
is a director, actor, writer,
and comedian, best known

00:00:20.970 --> 00:00:24.000
for his cult classics
"Super Troopers,"

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.580
"Club Dread," and "Beerfest."

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.580
He has also directed for
numerous popular TV shows,

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:32.130
including "Arrested
Development," "Community,"

00:00:32.130 --> 00:00:35.820
"Chuck," "The Grinder,"
"New Girl," and "Psych."

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:38.650
Currently, he's on tour
promoting his new book

00:00:38.650 --> 00:00:41.310
"Mustache Shenanigans,"
as well as

00:00:41.310 --> 00:00:44.910
promoting his highly anticipated
release of "Super Troopers 2,"

00:00:44.910 --> 00:00:46.530
set to launch later this year.

00:00:46.530 --> 00:00:48.618
Please welcome me
in introducing Jay.

00:00:48.618 --> 00:00:50.112
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:08.070 --> 00:01:09.250
Welcome to Google.

00:01:09.250 --> 00:01:09.940
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
Thank you very much.

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:11.189
ALLAN WEINBERGER: How are you?

00:01:11.189 --> 00:01:14.040
So before the movies and before
your comedy troupe Broken

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:17.820
Lizard, you were actually born
and raised here in Chicago.

00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:21.090
Did you grow up with
a comedic upbringing?

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:22.770
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
I mean, you know, I

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:26.400
grew up in the suburbs
of Chicago in Hinsdale.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:31.050
And my friend's
brothers introduced us

00:01:31.050 --> 00:01:34.500
to "Monty Python
and the Holy Grail"

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:37.060
and also introduced
us to The Beatles.

00:01:37.060 --> 00:01:40.040
And so that was sort
of the beginning

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:45.255
of thinking about what a
comedy group was all about.

00:01:45.255 --> 00:01:48.660
I remember listening to
the Steve Martin album

00:01:48.660 --> 00:01:51.090
"Let's Get Small."

00:01:51.090 --> 00:01:55.340
And then I saw the Richard
Pryor concert film "Live."

00:01:55.340 --> 00:01:56.340
It's Richard Pryor live.

00:01:56.340 --> 00:01:57.464
It's the one in Long Beach.

00:01:57.464 --> 00:02:01.320
And that is I think the best
recorded stand-up that's

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:04.680
ever been put on film.

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:10.530
When I was 15, my dad took
me to the Chicago Theatre

00:02:10.530 --> 00:02:12.584
to see Eddie Murphy in concert.

00:02:12.584 --> 00:02:13.500
ALLAN WEINBERGER: Wow.

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:16.200
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: It was the
"Delirious" tour, and it was--

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:19.620
we sat in the very back
row of the Chicago Theatre.

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:21.780
And I was like, that's a job?

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:24.120
I mean, wow.

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:27.960
So that's sort of the
beginnings for me.

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:29.790
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
And then you were

00:02:29.790 --> 00:02:33.630
a traditional-- you went to
Colgate and started up comedy.

00:02:33.630 --> 00:02:35.610
But when did you
say, like, you know

00:02:35.610 --> 00:02:41.340
what, I'm going to really push
this comedy thing full-time?

00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:43.890
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
Well, I was at Colgate

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:46.030
and I had been a writer and--

00:02:46.030 --> 00:02:46.530
I'm sorry.

00:02:46.530 --> 00:02:49.150
I had been an actor in
high school and college.

00:02:49.150 --> 00:02:50.980
I had been in a lot of plays.

00:02:50.980 --> 00:02:53.880
Am I supposed to
talk to them or you?

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:55.330
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
You know what--

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:56.540
to all of us, to everybody.

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:56.870
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: OK.

00:02:56.870 --> 00:02:57.240
ALLAN WEINBERGER: Sure.

00:02:57.240 --> 00:02:57.820
To them.

00:02:57.820 --> 00:02:58.840
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: I've been
talking to you all afternoon.

00:02:58.840 --> 00:02:59.330
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:02:59.330 --> 00:03:00.163
We've been together.

00:03:00.163 --> 00:03:02.370
He did a Reddit
AMA earlier today

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:04.410
and I was able to
sit in on that.

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:06.390
I kind of felt like a
voyeur-- kind of weird--

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:09.500
but it was fun to
watch from that side.

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:10.972
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Thank you.

00:03:10.972 --> 00:03:13.390
It was fun to have
you watching me.

00:03:13.390 --> 00:03:14.515
ALLAN WEINBERGER: Yeah.

00:03:14.515 --> 00:03:15.140
Thank you, Jay.

00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:22.650
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: I can't
remember the question.

00:03:22.650 --> 00:03:23.730
Oh, yeah, I remember now.

00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:25.350
I was a writer and--

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:26.400
shit, I wasn't a writer.

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:29.730
I was an actor in high
school and college.

00:03:29.730 --> 00:03:34.320
And I was in a lot of plays,
like "Death of a Salesman."

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.070
I was Tony in "West Side Story."

00:03:38.070 --> 00:03:39.660
You know, because
in the theater,

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:41.760
it's all race-blind casting.

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:45.150
But when I looked at
the movie screens,

00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:47.627
I noticed that there
were no Indians on them

00:03:47.627 --> 00:03:48.960
and there were no Indians in TV.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:50.709
I mean, Ben Kingsley
had won for "Gandhi,"

00:03:50.709 --> 00:03:54.390
but I didn't think they were
going to take a "Gandhi 2."

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:56.910
and they weren't going to cast
me in it, that's for sure.

00:03:56.910 --> 00:04:02.370
So I was not sure
about showbusiness.

00:04:02.370 --> 00:04:04.710
It seemed like a really
stupid idea for an Indian guy.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.560
Also, you know, I had gotten
a lot of laughs in plays

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:14.730
that I had done in school, but
your friends laughing at you

00:04:14.730 --> 00:04:15.400
is one thing.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:18.000
But I decided I'd give
myself a test, which

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.420
was to find out if I could
make strangers laugh.

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:26.610
And so at Colgate,
juniors, a lot of them

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:31.290
go off to Europe or China
or somewhere and study.

00:04:31.290 --> 00:04:34.440
I went and took a semester at
Loyola University in Chicago,

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:39.569
and I joined up with the
Improv Olympic, which is--

00:04:39.569 --> 00:04:40.610
ALLAN WEINBERGER: Now iO.

00:04:40.610 --> 00:04:41.818
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: iO, right.

00:04:41.818 --> 00:04:45.620
And I got into a beginning--

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:47.490
well, it was like
an improv class

00:04:47.490 --> 00:04:49.060
taught by this guy
Del Close, who's

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:51.090
sort of the father of improv.

00:04:51.090 --> 00:04:53.010
Chris Farley was in
that class at the time.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:57.810
He was in the highest
group and his shows

00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:01.590
with guys like Dave Koechner
and that were poetic.

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:03.720
I mean, they were amazing.

00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:06.930
My shows, which were with
the beginning improvisers who

00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:10.200
had just signed up,
were a grinding,

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:14.250
awful 45 minutes of silence.

00:05:14.250 --> 00:05:17.440
I was not making strangers
laugh in this improv.

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:19.960
I mean, our group, it was awful.

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:25.110
And so I said, well, I'm
not passing my test here.

00:05:25.110 --> 00:05:27.615
So I thought about--

00:05:27.615 --> 00:05:30.980
I'm like, OK, I'm going to
write some stand-up jokes.

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:32.910
So I wrote 10 minutes
of stand-up jokes.

00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:34.020
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
That's a lot of minutes.

00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:35.020
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Yeah.

00:05:35.020 --> 00:05:36.540
I mean, they said
you had to do 10.

00:05:36.540 --> 00:05:38.555
So I signed up for an open mic.

00:05:38.555 --> 00:05:40.680
And I went to a place called
the Match Stick, which

00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:42.150
I think was in Lincoln Park.

00:05:42.150 --> 00:05:44.530
And I went up on
a Tuesday night.

00:05:44.530 --> 00:05:48.870
I drank like four Tom Collins,
which was inexplicably

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:49.860
my drink at the time.

00:05:53.390 --> 00:06:00.791
I went into the awful
bathroom of that place

00:06:00.791 --> 00:06:02.040
and had a nerve shit, frankly.

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:07.500
And then they called
my name, and I went up

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:12.000
and I did my 10 minutes of
stand-up in about five minutes.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:13.140
I just raced through it.

00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:14.760
I'm like, I got to
get off the stage.

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:16.890
But I got laughs.

00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:18.780
Strangers were laughing.

00:06:18.780 --> 00:06:20.510
And I'm like, OK, OK.

00:06:20.510 --> 00:06:23.700
And so over the next
semester, I did--

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:25.320
another 20 times, I went up.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:29.150
And sometimes I would kill,
and sometimes I would bomb,

00:06:29.150 --> 00:06:31.260
and it was the same exact jokes.

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:35.010
And I found out that the more--

00:06:35.010 --> 00:06:40.130
if I memorized every single
line, every breath, every look,

00:06:40.130 --> 00:06:42.630
I would bomb.

00:06:42.630 --> 00:06:47.552
Sometimes they'd be like,
OK, you're going up sixth,

00:06:47.552 --> 00:06:48.760
and they'd call me up second.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:49.610
And I'm like ah.

00:06:49.610 --> 00:06:51.693
And they'd already called
you up, you're like, ah.

00:06:51.693 --> 00:06:53.335
And you go up,
usually I would kill.

00:06:53.335 --> 00:06:54.960
And I talked to my
mom, and she's like,

00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:58.582
you know, you're telling
these jokes and they need to--

00:06:58.582 --> 00:07:00.540
it should be like you're
in a bar telling jokes

00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:01.206
to your friends.

00:07:01.206 --> 00:07:03.390
It needs to feel spontaneous.

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:06.630
It's probably too canned
when you memorize.

00:07:06.630 --> 00:07:08.880
I mean, it's one of those
few jobs where the more you

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:11.045
prepare, the worse you are.

00:07:11.045 --> 00:07:12.420
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
I felt that way

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:14.820
with trying to pronounce
your name today.

00:07:14.820 --> 00:07:17.910
I said it in the mirror
probably 100 times,

00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:19.770
and the only time it
mattered, I fumbled.

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:20.480
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
Yeah, you botched it.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:21.386
ALLAN WEINBERGER: Yeah, yeah.

00:07:21.386 --> 00:07:22.470
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
You really botched it.

00:07:22.470 --> 00:07:24.886
ALLAN WEINBERGER: I should've
just walked up and tried it.

00:07:24.886 --> 00:07:26.550
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Yeah.

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:29.430
ALLAN WEINBERGER: So your
book "Mustache Shenanigans"--

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:31.930
which it is available here.

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:33.320
Google has subsidized the rate.

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:35.600
So if anyone would like them,
you can get them signed.

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:37.020
I think there's an
audiobook as well.

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:37.830
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Yeah.

00:07:37.830 --> 00:07:38.790
ALLAN WEINBERGER: We don't
sell the audiobook here,

00:07:38.790 --> 00:07:40.460
but you can get that online.

00:07:40.460 --> 00:07:42.870
In the book, you talk a
lot about "Super Troopers"

00:07:42.870 --> 00:07:44.070
and the making of it.

00:07:44.070 --> 00:07:46.110
And one part that I
found really interesting

00:07:46.110 --> 00:07:49.410
is that you actually
had access--

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:50.670
with the original script--

00:07:50.670 --> 00:07:53.850
to a lot of these production
houses and Miramax.

00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:56.370
And Harvey Weinstein
gave it a read,

00:07:56.370 --> 00:07:58.110
and ultimately turned it down--

00:07:58.110 --> 00:08:00.360
and a series of turndowns.

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:04.159
How did you guys
feel with this--

00:08:04.159 --> 00:08:05.700
you know, you knew
you had something,

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:07.620
but it was getting
rejected all the time.

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:08.578
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Bad.

00:08:10.670 --> 00:08:13.530
We made a film called
"Puddle Cruiser" first.

00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:18.690
And we went to Sundance and
we had amazing screenings--

00:08:18.690 --> 00:08:20.630
like packed houses, huge laughs.

00:08:20.630 --> 00:08:22.490
People were like,
who are these guys?

00:08:22.490 --> 00:08:24.380
And yet the film didn't sell.

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:27.430
And eventually it did sell, but
it didn't sell out of Sundance.

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:29.690
And we were like, now what?

00:08:29.690 --> 00:08:31.220
So we wrote the script--

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:33.647
I mean, what happened was
Miramax flirted with buying it.

00:08:33.647 --> 00:08:34.730
He flirted with buying it.

00:08:34.730 --> 00:08:37.370
And Harvey just was
never in the room

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:40.614
when we had a big screening.

00:08:40.614 --> 00:08:42.530
His staff is like, you
have to buy this movie.

00:08:42.530 --> 00:08:44.570
And he goes, yeah,
set up a screening.

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:47.000
We'd set up a huge screening,
it'd get huge laughs,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:48.050
he wouldn't show up.

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:51.020
And finally, he saw
it alone in his office

00:08:51.020 --> 00:08:52.550
and he really liked it.

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:58.502
So he called me and he said,
this is a really good movie.

00:08:58.502 --> 00:08:59.960
I want to make a
TV show out of it.

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:01.640
And I'm like, why don't
we just set up a screening

00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:02.930
and you can watch it,
and you can buy it?

00:09:02.930 --> 00:09:04.760
And he goes, OK, we'll
set up a screening.

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:07.700
So we set up a screening
and we did the screening

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:10.100
on 3rd Street and
11th Avenue, which

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:13.350
is right next to
NYU, where there

00:09:13.350 --> 00:09:14.660
are a lot of film students.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:16.130
And so we had this
big screening.

00:09:16.130 --> 00:09:18.530
And, of course, Harvey
doesn't show up.

00:09:18.530 --> 00:09:20.430
And the screening kills.

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:21.590
It's just great laughter.

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:23.881
His executives are like, it's
killing, you got to come.

00:09:23.881 --> 00:09:25.520
So he comes and
arrives at the end

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:27.811
of the screening, which is
when the question and answer

00:09:27.811 --> 00:09:28.850
with the audiences.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:30.260
The audience is
loving the movie.

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:31.760
They're like, this
is a great movie.

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:33.860
It's about people
our age and da da da.

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:37.310
Then Harvey walks in, and one
by one these film students

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:40.100
look back and see the
king of independent film

00:09:40.100 --> 00:09:42.110
and they all turn into
basically Pauline Kael.

00:09:42.110 --> 00:09:46.370
And they're like, the framing
wasn't great on that one shot.

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:48.310
And they all start
trashing the movie.

00:09:48.310 --> 00:09:49.730
They're like, we didn't
buy the characters.

00:09:49.730 --> 00:09:50.563
And you're like, uh.

00:09:50.563 --> 00:09:52.370
And he's like, sorry, kid.

00:09:52.370 --> 00:09:55.510
He goes, but let's try
again on a new one.

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:57.830
And so he goes, bring me
the next script, I'll buy it

00:09:57.830 --> 00:09:59.720
and we'll make that movie.

00:09:59.720 --> 00:10:01.070
We wrote "Super Troopers."

00:10:01.070 --> 00:10:03.530
And we wrote, like, 10
drafts of this thing,

00:10:03.530 --> 00:10:05.380
and it got pretty damn good.

00:10:05.380 --> 00:10:07.880
And his executives are like,
we're going to make this movie.

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:09.620
We gave it to Harvey.

00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:11.930
He read it, and
he said, you know,

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:13.370
I don't know if it's funny.

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:15.710
And he goes, but don't feel
bad because I usually can't

00:10:15.710 --> 00:10:17.800
tell when something's funny.

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:21.050
And I'm like, OK.

00:10:21.050 --> 00:10:22.850
So he goes, but I'm
going to let you

00:10:22.850 --> 00:10:25.810
have it back if you want to
go make it somewhere else.

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:26.900
He didn't have to do that.

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:27.580
He could have--

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:27.940
ALLAN WEINBERGER: They
can table it, right?

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.170
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Most
presidents of studios

00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:31.280
just sit on it.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:33.394
They're like, I'm
not going to make it,

00:10:33.394 --> 00:10:35.060
but I don't want
someone else to make it

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:36.380
because then I'll look bad.

00:10:36.380 --> 00:10:39.480
So they usually just sit on it
and just stick it in a vault.

00:10:39.480 --> 00:10:43.340
But he let me have it
back because he liked me.

00:10:43.340 --> 00:10:46.130
And then we went
around to everybody--

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:49.960
Warner Brothers,
Paramount, Universal.

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:53.297
They said, we'll make it.

00:10:53.297 --> 00:10:55.130
They were going to make
it for $5.5 million,

00:10:55.130 --> 00:10:58.094
but the producer then
couldn't work out his pay

00:10:58.094 --> 00:10:58.760
and it was over.

00:10:58.760 --> 00:10:59.420
It was out.

00:10:59.420 --> 00:11:01.460
We were green lit,
and then we were not.

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:03.019
So then the Farrelly
brothers called.

00:11:03.019 --> 00:11:03.560
They read it.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:06.320
They said, this movie would
work if it was set in the '70s.

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:07.730
And we're like, OK.

00:11:07.730 --> 00:11:10.340
So we wrote the
'70s version, and it

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:13.110
was called "Super Trooper '76."

00:11:13.110 --> 00:11:14.360
Then Fox read it.

00:11:14.360 --> 00:11:16.421
They're like, yeah,
it's good, but you guys

00:11:16.421 --> 00:11:17.420
are going to star in it?

00:11:17.420 --> 00:11:18.740
I don't think so.

00:11:18.740 --> 00:11:19.850
And we're like, OK.

00:11:19.850 --> 00:11:22.330
So then nobody would finance it.

00:11:22.330 --> 00:11:24.824
Then we went to all the
independent financers

00:11:24.824 --> 00:11:26.240
and we met with a
bunch of people.

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:28.430
One guy was like, I'll
give you the money

00:11:28.430 --> 00:11:30.470
if Ben Affleck can play Thorny.

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:32.450
And I'm like, I'm
playing Thorny.

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:35.690
He goes, not in this
movie, you're not.

00:11:35.690 --> 00:11:37.010
And I'm like--

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:38.840
So we really struck out.

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:41.660
Nobody would finance
the movie, basically

00:11:41.660 --> 00:11:44.570
because we weren't stars.

00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:47.210
Broken Lizard was basically
about to break up.

00:11:47.210 --> 00:11:48.440
We packed up our office.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:51.350
I was packing up my office and
I was going to move out to LA

00:11:51.350 --> 00:11:53.900
and just try to audition
and see what happens.

00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:58.190
And I was packing my
office and the phone rang,

00:11:58.190 --> 00:12:00.530
and it was my friend Cricket
who I went to college with.

00:12:00.530 --> 00:12:04.880
And she said, I hate to ask
you, but my dad's a banker,

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:08.330
and he's retiring and he
wants to write movie scripts.

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:11.180
And you're the only guy
who's sort of making movies,

00:12:11.180 --> 00:12:13.665
so I told him about you and
he wants to talk to you.

00:12:13.665 --> 00:12:14.540
And I said, OK, sure.

00:12:14.540 --> 00:12:18.590
So I talked to him and he
goes, I wrote this script,

00:12:18.590 --> 00:12:22.550
and it's like a girl
comedy road movie

00:12:22.550 --> 00:12:24.629
and I'm wondering if
you could take a read.

00:12:24.629 --> 00:12:26.420
And I'm like, yeah,
sure, I'll take a read.

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:28.961
And he goes, actually, before
I send it to you, why don't you

00:12:28.961 --> 00:12:30.650
send me a sample of
your stuff so I just

00:12:30.650 --> 00:12:33.710
know what your style is.

00:12:33.710 --> 00:12:35.210
And I'm like, oh,
you're auditioning

00:12:35.210 --> 00:12:37.010
me to read your script.

00:12:37.010 --> 00:12:38.970
OK, got it.

00:12:38.970 --> 00:12:40.830
So I sent him "Super
Troopers" and I'm like,

00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:42.538
I hope he doesn't like
it because I don't

00:12:42.538 --> 00:12:43.940
want to read his damn script.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:47.510
And he calls me a week later.

00:12:47.510 --> 00:12:50.052
And he's like, this
thing's pretty funny.

00:12:50.052 --> 00:12:51.260
And I said, oh, yeah, thanks.

00:12:51.260 --> 00:12:52.635
He goes, what's
going on with it?

00:12:52.635 --> 00:12:56.315
And I'm like, well, nothing.

00:12:56.315 --> 00:12:57.440
Nothing's going on with it.

00:12:57.440 --> 00:12:58.670
We can't get any
money to make it.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:00.860
And he goes, can you make
it for a million dollars?

00:13:00.860 --> 00:13:03.417
And I said, yeah.

00:13:03.417 --> 00:13:05.750
And he said, all right, I'll
give you a million dollars.

00:13:05.750 --> 00:13:09.140
And I said, oh, OK.

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:12.920
And three weeks later we
were casting the movie.

00:13:12.920 --> 00:13:20.330
And the movie sold for about
$3.25 million at Sundance.

00:13:20.330 --> 00:13:24.750
I mean, he's made nine times
his investment on that movie.

00:13:24.750 --> 00:13:28.320
Nobody in showbusiness
thought it was a good bet.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:32.647
And this guy's like, OK,
and then there he goes.

00:13:32.647 --> 00:13:34.230
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
So the movie went on

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:37.650
to make about $80 million--

00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:40.790
well worth the investment there.

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:43.500
So "Super Troopers 2" is
coming out later this year.

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:44.010
Is that--

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:45.060
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: In
the next six months.

00:13:45.060 --> 00:13:46.935
ALLAN WEINBERGER: In
the next six months, OK.

00:13:46.935 --> 00:13:48.570
And you guys did
something unique.

00:13:48.570 --> 00:13:51.084
You went the route
of crowdfunding it.

00:13:51.084 --> 00:13:52.500
Now, with such a
successful movie,

00:13:52.500 --> 00:13:54.990
you'd think these movie houses
would be banging down your door

00:13:54.990 --> 00:13:56.031
to get in on this action.

00:13:56.031 --> 00:13:58.102
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
You would think.

00:13:58.102 --> 00:13:59.310
ALLAN WEINBERGER: Fill me in.

00:13:59.310 --> 00:14:01.140
Why'd you go the route
of crowdsourcing--

00:14:01.140 --> 00:14:02.850
or crowdfunding?

00:14:02.850 --> 00:14:05.100
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: I mean,
the first film was a shock,

00:14:05.100 --> 00:14:08.640
I think, to the studio, and
it continues to be a shock.

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:11.470
I mean, they listed it--

00:14:11.470 --> 00:14:12.940
this was a number of years ago.

00:14:12.940 --> 00:14:14.324
It was probably
five, six years--

00:14:14.324 --> 00:14:15.240
maybe eight years ago.

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:18.990
They listed it on why Fox
had had such a good year.

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:21.869
It was "Star Wars,"
"Super Troopers."

00:14:21.869 --> 00:14:23.910
I mean, this was like 10
years after it came out.

00:14:23.910 --> 00:14:26.520
It was still just
churning money for them.

00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:29.700
And so we were like, OK.

00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:33.810
But there was so much
money made that we had--

00:14:33.810 --> 00:14:36.330
and they, of course, were
like, oh, it didn't really

00:14:36.330 --> 00:14:37.780
make that much.

00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:39.825
And of course that's
the dance in Hollywood.

00:14:39.825 --> 00:14:41.580
The studio's like,
oh, where's the money?

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:42.540
We don't know.

00:14:42.540 --> 00:14:45.296
And then you audit them, and
then someone says, OK, this

00:14:45.296 --> 00:14:46.420
is how much it really made.

00:14:46.420 --> 00:14:47.711
You have to write them a check.

00:14:47.711 --> 00:14:49.110
That's how it works.

00:14:49.110 --> 00:14:51.302
And we all know it, and
we're all fine with it.

00:14:51.302 --> 00:14:52.260
That's just what we do.

00:14:55.650 --> 00:14:56.700
There was a debate--

00:14:56.700 --> 00:14:59.040
there was an argument about
how much the profit was.

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:03.930
And so it was locked up
in a legal issue that

00:15:03.930 --> 00:15:06.330
went on for four or five years.

00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:07.290
And so it took a while.

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:10.320
And out of the settlement--

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:12.930
part of it was, OK,
you can make the movie.

00:15:12.930 --> 00:15:18.600
But while that was happening,
the entire film business

00:15:18.600 --> 00:15:20.760
became a business
that only wanted

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:23.760
to make movies where the main
characters were in tights

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:25.590
and wore capes.

00:15:25.590 --> 00:15:29.650
That was the only kind of movie
they wanted to make at all.

00:15:29.650 --> 00:15:34.860
And so when we went to ask them
to make it, they were like--

00:15:34.860 --> 00:15:38.310
they said, look, we know
the sequel will make money,

00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:40.680
we just don't know if
it'll make enough money.

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:43.330
And I'll give you an
example, a story here.

00:15:46.330 --> 00:15:47.670
I had a deal at Warner Brothers.

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:50.410
And I went into the
president of Warner Brothers,

00:15:50.410 --> 00:15:54.680
and he said, what kind of
movies are we going to make?

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:58.140
He goes, I want to make
$100 million comedies

00:15:58.140 --> 00:15:59.820
with any of these two stars--

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:08.970
Johnny Depp, Ben Stiller,
Vince Vaughn, and Will Ferrell.

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:10.290
That's the whole list.

00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:15.300
And I was like, OK, what
if instead we make five

00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:18.450
$20-million movies and we'll
put some up-and-comers in it,

00:16:18.450 --> 00:16:19.720
like Broken Lizard?

00:16:19.720 --> 00:16:26.040
And you know, whatever, we'll
make some cheaper movies

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:28.440
and we'll be able
to make more of them

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:29.990
and we'll make
them more quickly.

00:16:29.990 --> 00:16:32.820
And he goes, what's the most one
of those $20-million movies can

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:33.320
make?

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:35.910
And I said, $100 million.

00:16:35.910 --> 00:16:37.440
That's a $80-million profit.

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:40.350
And he goes, that's a double.

00:16:40.350 --> 00:16:42.810
He goes, we need
movies that will

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:45.740
gross $250 to $400 million.

00:16:45.740 --> 00:16:46.770
We need grand slams.

00:16:46.770 --> 00:16:49.554
We need movies that will
move the stock price.

00:16:49.554 --> 00:16:50.220
And I was like--

00:16:50.220 --> 00:16:51.420
ALLAN WEINBERGER: That sounds
like working at Google.

00:16:51.420 --> 00:16:53.850
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Well,
that's the problem,

00:16:53.850 --> 00:16:56.880
is that corporations
bought movie companies

00:16:56.880 --> 00:16:59.610
because they wanted a
fun little media piece.

00:16:59.610 --> 00:17:02.010
And then they saw
what "Iron Man" did

00:17:02.010 --> 00:17:05.579
and they saw what these
really great superhero movies

00:17:05.579 --> 00:17:09.339
are doing is making so much
money that the whole industry

00:17:09.339 --> 00:17:12.000
has turned towards them only.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.255
But to the exclusion of--

00:17:14.255 --> 00:17:15.630
And I'll tell you,
the reason why

00:17:15.630 --> 00:17:17.940
is because you
can take an action

00:17:17.940 --> 00:17:22.650
film with a guy in tights and a
cape, and it can play in China,

00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:25.960
it can play in India, it
can play all over the world.

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:29.130
The Chinese don't get
what meow versus--

00:17:29.130 --> 00:17:29.880
they don't get it.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:31.020
They're like, what?

00:17:31.020 --> 00:17:33.340
What's funny about that?

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:36.930
And so the movies don't
travel well there,

00:17:36.930 --> 00:17:39.770
and so there's a ceiling
on what comedies can make.

00:17:39.770 --> 00:17:42.280
And as a result, they
don't to make them.

00:17:42.280 --> 00:17:44.050
So it's the same with--

00:17:44.050 --> 00:17:46.050
they don't make movies
like "Kramer vs. Kramer,"

00:17:46.050 --> 00:17:49.380
they don't make movies
like "Breaking Away,"

00:17:49.380 --> 00:17:52.050
these smaller $20 to
$50-million movies.

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:54.900
They're like, no, no, put
them in a cape and the tights,

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:56.280
or we're out.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:17:59.220
And so with "Super Troopers
2," I know they probably

00:17:59.220 --> 00:18:01.290
had a conversation
where they're like,

00:18:01.290 --> 00:18:04.140
do you think we could put
the "Super Troopers" in capes

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:06.210
and make them "Super" Troopers?

00:18:06.210 --> 00:18:09.360
I mean, I'm sure they
had that conversation.

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:13.646
So they said, guys, go raise
the money and make the movie

00:18:13.646 --> 00:18:14.520
and we'll release it.

00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:18.270
Which, by the way, is a huge
gift to give us a release slot.

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:20.310
It's amazing.

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:21.300
So we did that.

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:24.960
And we decided to go to
a crowdfunding site--

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:27.060
Indiegogo-- and see if
we could raise money.

00:18:27.060 --> 00:18:32.010
And the risk was if the audience
was like, nah, who cares,

00:18:32.010 --> 00:18:34.560
we don't want to see a
sequel, it's been too long,

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:37.020
or whatever, then the
movie would have died

00:18:37.020 --> 00:18:39.530
because the studio would
have been like, god,

00:18:39.530 --> 00:18:42.480
nobody wants to see this.

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:47.100
But we raised $2 million in
24 hours and $4.7 million

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:48.030
over 30 days.

00:18:48.030 --> 00:18:51.390
And after that, we were able
to raise a bunch more money

00:18:51.390 --> 00:18:53.130
to make the film.

00:18:53.130 --> 00:18:54.450
ALLAN WEINBERGER: So it's done?

00:18:54.450 --> 00:18:55.324
It's ready to launch?

00:18:55.324 --> 00:18:57.117
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: It's done.

00:18:57.117 --> 00:18:57.950
The editing is done.

