So first off, go 'Gate.

00:31:54.420 --> 00:31:56.310
So fellow Colgate alum.

00:31:56.310 --> 00:31:57.960
And I've always
wondered this and been

00:31:57.960 --> 00:31:59.850
asked this a lot-- because
coming from Chicago,

00:31:59.850 --> 00:32:01.474
people used to ask
why you would end up

00:32:01.474 --> 00:32:03.180
in Upstate New York to me.

00:32:03.180 --> 00:32:05.010
And I'm wondering,
for you-- who I

00:32:05.010 --> 00:32:06.551
would assume at the
time you probably

00:32:06.551 --> 00:32:09.190
had a sense of the dramatic
arts is where you wanted to go--

00:32:09.190 --> 00:32:12.540
and obviously New York and
NYU or Northwestern or USC

00:32:12.540 --> 00:32:15.891
might have seemed like more
logical solutions for that.

00:32:15.891 --> 00:32:17.640
How did you end up at
a small liberal arts

00:32:17.640 --> 00:32:20.400
school in Upstate New
York versus a more

00:32:20.400 --> 00:32:22.950
traditional dramatic program?

00:32:22.950 --> 00:32:25.110
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: How
I ended up at Colgate,

00:32:25.110 --> 00:32:28.570
which ended up
shaping my whole life,

00:32:28.570 --> 00:32:34.110
is one of the great
flukes in my story.

00:32:34.110 --> 00:32:35.860
Colgate, for those of
you that don't know,

00:32:35.860 --> 00:32:38.030
it's got 2,750 students.

00:32:38.030 --> 00:32:42.230
It's 3 and 1/2 hours
north of New York City.

00:32:42.230 --> 00:32:44.690
It's a beautiful--
it's a great school.

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:46.970
It's like number
19 in the country.

00:32:46.970 --> 00:32:49.790
And it's surrounded
by farmland basically,

00:32:49.790 --> 00:32:51.050
but it's a beautiful place.

00:32:51.050 --> 00:32:53.960
It wins the most beautiful
campus in the country

00:32:53.960 --> 00:32:55.890
almost every year.

00:32:55.890 --> 00:33:02.120
And so I, in high school, had
a very high opinion of myself.

00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:07.790
I really-- while I didn't have
the grades to get into the Ivy

00:33:07.790 --> 00:33:12.050
League, I thought, they're
going to let me in anyway.

00:33:12.050 --> 00:33:16.460
And so I applied to Harvard,
Yale, Stanford, Dartmouth,

00:33:16.460 --> 00:33:21.800
I applied to Northwestern,
and Brown, and that's it.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:28.490
And I was like, yeah and my
grade point average was B-plus.

00:33:28.490 --> 00:33:33.320
And I'm like, OK, but they're
going to love my personality

00:33:33.320 --> 00:33:35.000
and they're going to love my--

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:35.930
I'm going to get in.

00:33:35.930 --> 00:33:42.790
And so I started to second-guess
myself late in January.

00:33:42.790 --> 00:33:44.480
I'm like, I'm a little worried.

00:33:44.480 --> 00:33:46.410
What happens if I
don't get in anywhere?

00:33:46.410 --> 00:33:48.170
And I'm walking down
the hallway and I

00:33:48.170 --> 00:33:50.991
happen to run into my
girlfriend at the time.

00:33:50.991 --> 00:33:53.240
And I said, you know, I'm a
little nervous about where

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:54.114
I applied to schools.

00:33:54.114 --> 00:33:56.540
I said, do you have any
applications in your locker?

00:33:56.540 --> 00:33:58.040
And she goes,
yeah, I think I do.

00:33:58.040 --> 00:33:59.960
And so we go to her
locker and she pulls out

00:33:59.960 --> 00:34:03.039
one for Boston College, Boston
University, and Colgate.

00:34:03.039 --> 00:34:04.580
And I look at them,
and I'm like, OK,

00:34:04.580 --> 00:34:06.280
my essay can fit these.

00:34:06.280 --> 00:34:07.584
So I ran around to my teachers.

00:34:07.584 --> 00:34:09.209
I'm like, you got to
send it out today.

00:34:09.209 --> 00:34:11.276
They send out recommendations.

00:34:11.276 --> 00:34:12.650
The three schools
that I got into

00:34:12.650 --> 00:34:16.810
were Boston College, Boston
University, and Colgate.

00:34:16.810 --> 00:34:23.739
And with all of
the A-plus Indians

00:34:23.739 --> 00:34:25.989
that these schools
had to sift through,

00:34:25.989 --> 00:34:28.760
they certainly didn't want
this junky old B-plus Indian.

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:34.730
I mean, they're like, why would
we take you, B-plus Indian?

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:39.590
And so I looked at
the rankings and I'm

00:34:39.590 --> 00:34:42.770
like, OK, Colgate's higher than
these other two, I'll go there.

00:34:42.770 --> 00:34:44.690
And so that's why
I went to Colgate.

00:34:44.690 --> 00:34:48.230
And it's the greatest
place on earth.

00:34:48.230 --> 00:34:51.325
I mean, I loved that
place more than--

00:34:51.325 --> 00:34:54.108
I only cry about once a decade.

00:34:54.108 --> 00:34:54.649
I don't know.

00:34:54.649 --> 00:34:58.010
I have very dry tear ducts.

00:34:58.010 --> 00:35:03.495
And I wept at the
bar on the last night

00:35:03.495 --> 00:35:05.370
when I had to leave
there because I loved it.

00:35:05.370 --> 00:35:06.980
It's still my favorite place.

00:35:06.980 --> 00:35:08.600
AUDIENCE: Can I ask which bar?

00:35:08.600 --> 00:35:09.080
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: The Jug.

00:35:09.080 --> 00:35:09.890
AUDIENCE: Yeah, there we go.

00:35:09.890 --> 00:35:10.790
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: There
are two bars in town--

00:35:10.790 --> 00:35:11.870
The Jug and The [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:11.870 --> 00:35:13.490
AUDIENCE: I was like, it's
that or The [? Bacon, ?] yeah.

00:35:13.490 --> 00:35:13.700
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Yeah.

00:35:13.700 --> 00:35:14.577
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:35:14.577 --> 00:35:15.410
AUDIENCE: Hey there.

00:35:15.410 --> 00:35:17.540
I'm curious what
kind of response

00:35:17.540 --> 00:35:21.872
you got from patrolmen and
women and the police community.

00:35:21.872 --> 00:35:22.580
Did they like it?

00:35:22.580 --> 00:35:23.500
Did you capture it?

00:35:23.500 --> 00:35:24.440
Were they offended?

00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:26.120
What were some of
the best responses?

00:35:26.120 --> 00:35:29.870
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: We thought
we would be frequently arrested

00:35:29.870 --> 00:35:33.110
after we made that film.

00:35:33.110 --> 00:35:38.450
And it was sort of-- we didn't
really hear about anything much

00:35:38.450 --> 00:35:40.490
until we made "Beerfest."

00:35:40.490 --> 00:35:44.120
And we were down in Albuquerque
and we were making "Beerfest."

00:35:44.120 --> 00:35:46.670
And to try to get in
character, we basically

00:35:46.670 --> 00:35:50.030
had a beer pong
party every night.

00:35:50.030 --> 00:35:53.840
We were playing a lot of
beer pong, and we were loud.

00:35:53.840 --> 00:35:55.610
So we had these huge parties.

00:35:55.610 --> 00:36:00.260
And on like a Tuesday night,
there was a noise complaint.

00:36:00.260 --> 00:36:02.480
And there was a
knock on the door.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:04.550
I open the door,
and it's two cops.

00:36:04.550 --> 00:36:06.750
And I was like--

00:36:06.750 --> 00:36:10.200
look, I've always been
very polite to cops.

00:36:10.200 --> 00:36:13.620
And so I'm like,
hey, guys, so sorry.

00:36:13.620 --> 00:36:15.390
My apologies.

00:36:15.390 --> 00:36:18.250
And the cop looks at me and
then he looks at his partner

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:22.370
and he goes, you have
a good evening, sir.

00:36:22.370 --> 00:36:24.500
And they turn around
and walk away.

00:36:24.500 --> 00:36:26.460
And I'm like, OK.

00:36:26.460 --> 00:36:28.979
And so I close the door and
I'm like, I don't know what--

00:36:28.979 --> 00:36:30.020
they didn't say anything.

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:32.330
I said, they just left.

00:36:32.330 --> 00:36:33.380
And I'm like, OK.

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:36.170
10 minutes later, I open the
door again, another knock, it's

00:36:36.170 --> 00:36:36.890
seven cops.

00:36:39.590 --> 00:36:42.560
And the same guy
goes, can we come in

00:36:42.560 --> 00:36:45.071
and party with you, sir?

00:36:45.071 --> 00:36:47.470
And I was like, yeah.

00:36:47.470 --> 00:36:52.100
And I'm leading the pack,
I'm like, hide the bongs.

00:36:52.100 --> 00:36:55.490
And they stayed for
like a half an hour.

00:36:55.490 --> 00:36:58.640
And we just drank and
raged and had a great time.

00:36:58.640 --> 00:37:02.300
And it was then that I realized
that what they like about this

00:37:02.300 --> 00:37:03.920
movie is that they're--

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:09.890
mostly in Hollywood, we have
crooked cops and evil cops

00:37:09.890 --> 00:37:13.700
or really good cops who
are just super nice.

00:37:13.700 --> 00:37:16.370
We made human cops,
I think, to them.

00:37:16.370 --> 00:37:18.885
They feel human in our
film and they feel like--

00:37:18.885 --> 00:37:21.260
they are bored sometimes, they
do mess around with people

00:37:21.260 --> 00:37:21.759
sometimes.

00:37:21.759 --> 00:37:27.740
I mean, it has become
hard to get a ticket.

00:37:27.740 --> 00:37:31.820
We speed, they pull us over,
they walk up, they're like,

00:37:31.820 --> 00:37:32.889
oh, I'm sorry, sir.

00:37:32.889 --> 00:37:33.680
Are you in a hurry?

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:35.630
Do you need an escort somewhere?

00:37:35.630 --> 00:37:38.090
Kevin Heffernan,
he played Farva.

00:37:38.090 --> 00:37:40.670
We were throwing out the first
pitch in San Diego Qualcomm

00:37:40.670 --> 00:37:42.440
Stadium and he was late.

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:46.280
So he was driving 90 down
the 405, gets pulled over.

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:48.680
The cop says, oh my god, Farva!

00:37:48.680 --> 00:37:51.230
And he goes, I'm throwing
out the first pitch.

00:37:51.230 --> 00:37:52.550
He goes, follow me.

00:37:52.550 --> 00:37:58.010
They drive 105 down
to the stadium.

00:37:58.010 --> 00:37:59.960
Kevin doesn't know
where to park.

00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:02.430
The cop's like, just
stick it right there.

00:38:02.430 --> 00:38:05.960
And he gets out, and each
cop is like, I got him.

00:38:05.960 --> 00:38:09.920
And they're walking him
all the way into the mound.

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:11.130
It's amazing, right?

00:38:11.130 --> 00:38:11.990
It's amazing.

00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:13.115
AUDIENCE: That's fantastic.

00:38:13.115 --> 00:38:14.450
Thank you.

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:17.270
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if
there are any actual plans

00:38:17.270 --> 00:38:20.630
to release "Potfest," or
was that just a fun trailer

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:21.890
with Willie Nelson?

00:38:21.890 --> 00:38:24.223
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: They don't
have a drug testing policy

00:38:24.223 --> 00:38:25.790
here?

00:38:25.790 --> 00:38:29.035
Because test this guy.

00:38:29.035 --> 00:38:31.517
AUDIENCE: We actually don't
have a very strict drug testing

00:38:31.517 --> 00:38:32.792
policy.

00:38:32.792 --> 00:38:34.250
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
Well, at the end

00:38:34.250 --> 00:38:37.400
of "Beerfest," there's
a joke about "Potfest,"

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:38.420
which was a real joke.

00:38:38.420 --> 00:38:40.105
I mean, we were really kidding.

00:38:40.105 --> 00:38:41.480
But then there
are so many people

00:38:41.480 --> 00:38:44.690
who keep asking us
about making "Potfest."

00:38:44.690 --> 00:38:47.015
And then I've got to know a
lot of the famous stoners.

00:38:47.015 --> 00:38:49.250
I've gotten to know--

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:50.720
Willie, of course,
wants to do it.

00:38:50.720 --> 00:38:51.530
I met Snoop.

00:38:51.530 --> 00:38:52.940
He wants to do it.

00:38:52.940 --> 00:38:56.690
Cheech and Chong
both want to do it.

00:38:56.690 --> 00:38:59.420
Doug Benson wants to do it.

00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:02.070
We've written about
40 or 50 pages of it,

00:39:02.070 --> 00:39:07.790
but then we just get high
and lose our [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:07.790 --> 00:39:11.952
If we can ever focus and
get it done, we'll do it.

00:39:11.952 --> 00:39:14.750
We'll do it.

00:39:14.750 --> 00:39:16.750
AUDIENCE: So I thought
it was really interesting

00:39:16.750 --> 00:39:19.450
how you talked about Hollywood
wanting to do superhero movies.

00:39:19.450 --> 00:39:21.580
And I think those tend
to lend themselves

00:39:21.580 --> 00:39:23.980
to sequels that are all right.

00:39:23.980 --> 00:39:25.810
And I'm a huge
"Super Troopers" fan.

00:39:25.810 --> 00:39:27.580
Have you got a lot of flak
about that-- of like, all right,

00:39:27.580 --> 00:39:29.320
we're going to do
a sequel and I hope

00:39:29.320 --> 00:39:31.930
it doesn't ruin the first
one or anything like that?

00:39:31.930 --> 00:39:34.150
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
Yeah, from ourselves,

00:39:34.150 --> 00:39:36.760
because we have
the same feelings

00:39:36.760 --> 00:39:38.650
you do about certain sequels.

00:39:38.650 --> 00:39:42.920
We're like, should
we risk ruining it?

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:43.550
Yeah, we will.

00:39:46.080 --> 00:39:50.270
But ultimately what
we decided was--

00:39:50.270 --> 00:39:53.270
I told everybody--
it's been a while,

00:39:53.270 --> 00:39:56.000
so I said I'll only shoot
the movie if we're exactly

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:58.090
the same weight.

00:39:58.090 --> 00:40:01.310
So people will be able
to say, you look older,

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:03.170
but you don't look
fatter and older.

00:40:03.170 --> 00:40:05.900
I didn't want people to be able
to say you look fatter, too.

00:40:05.900 --> 00:40:10.700
So everybody got down to weight.

00:40:10.700 --> 00:40:15.140
And I also thought, let's
make the mustaches bigger.

00:40:15.140 --> 00:40:15.890
That'll help, too.

00:40:15.890 --> 00:40:17.630
So my mustache is
like twice the size.

00:40:20.300 --> 00:40:26.810
Ultimately, we really wanted
to just make another one.

00:40:26.810 --> 00:40:29.000
"NYPD Blue" made 200 episodes.

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.985
We can make two of these
damn things, right?

00:40:31.985 --> 00:40:36.090
I feel like the key is just
to keep the tone the same.

00:40:36.090 --> 00:40:38.510
And I know that tone.

00:40:38.510 --> 00:40:40.850
I rewatched the movie
before I shot it.

00:40:40.850 --> 00:40:45.980
And I'm like, OK, tough,
funny, try to make it smart,

00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:48.860
make all the jokes make
sense, and keep all the jokes

00:40:48.860 --> 00:40:51.260
within a certain bandwidth.

00:40:51.260 --> 00:40:54.330
Everything has to feel
like it's possible.

00:40:54.330 --> 00:40:56.810
Everything has to
feel like it's real.

00:40:56.810 --> 00:41:01.220
And cast good actors who
know their way around a joke.

00:41:01.220 --> 00:41:03.980
And I was worried about it.

00:41:03.980 --> 00:41:06.950
But I mean, we've now shown
it to about 500 people

00:41:06.950 --> 00:41:11.180
in California at three or
four 200-person screenings,

00:41:11.180 --> 00:41:14.720
and the response has
been incredibly good.

00:41:14.720 --> 00:41:16.790
So is it better than this one?

00:41:16.790 --> 00:41:17.630
Probably not.

00:41:17.630 --> 00:41:21.620
I mean, I think this movie
caught a certain wave that you

00:41:21.620 --> 00:41:23.720
can't necessarily recreate.

00:41:23.720 --> 00:41:27.450
But it has a ton of jokes in it.

00:41:27.450 --> 00:41:29.130
We wrote 30 drafts.

00:41:29.130 --> 00:41:30.800
We really worked hard on it.

00:41:30.800 --> 00:41:33.860
And I think you'll be able to
play the movies back to back

00:41:33.860 --> 00:41:36.049
and be like, yeah,
they're both good.

00:41:36.049 --> 00:41:37.090
AUDIENCE: That's awesome.

00:41:37.090 --> 00:41:40.575
And did you get pushed for any
cameos, speaking of casting

00:41:40.575 --> 00:41:41.450
and things like that?

00:41:41.450 --> 00:41:43.540
Or were people desperate
to get their hands on it?

00:41:43.540 --> 00:41:44.540
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Yeah.

00:41:44.540 --> 00:41:49.220
I mean, I was making a TV
show with Rob Lowe called

00:41:49.220 --> 00:41:53.480
"The Grinder" and we
got along really well.

00:41:53.480 --> 00:41:55.130
He's a really funny guy.

00:41:55.130 --> 00:41:57.920
He's like a comic trapped
in a leading man's body.

00:41:57.920 --> 00:42:00.620
He's just a funny, funny guy.

00:42:00.620 --> 00:42:02.940
And so I shot,
like, four of those.

00:42:02.940 --> 00:42:05.750
And then the last one,
we were in his trailer--

00:42:05.750 --> 00:42:09.380
whatever, he smokes cigars.

00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:12.020
And I got a part for him.

00:42:12.020 --> 00:42:15.590
And I just said, hey,
any chance you'd consider

00:42:15.590 --> 00:42:16.730
being in "Super Troopers."

00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:17.960
He goes, I'm in.

00:42:17.960 --> 00:42:20.300
I don't even have to
read the script, I'm in.

00:42:20.300 --> 00:42:23.720
And I was like, OK, great.

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:26.470
Everybody we asked said yes.

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:29.930
And so we've got some
fun people in it--

00:42:29.930 --> 00:42:33.230
people that fit
the roles, though.

00:42:33.230 --> 00:42:35.540
We don't just stick famous
people in movies because--

00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:43.110
The reason that movie is what it
is is because we picked a tone

00:42:43.110 --> 00:42:45.450
and we stuck to the tone.

00:42:45.450 --> 00:42:48.030
We don't just put any joke in.

00:42:48.030 --> 00:42:49.530
It has to fit the tone.

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:50.970
And the second
movie is the same.

00:42:50.970 --> 00:42:53.833
Every actor fits a tone,
every joke fits a tone.

00:42:53.833 --> 00:42:54.666
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:57.620 --> 00:42:59.690
ALLAN WEINBERGER: So
Jay, thank you very

00:42:59.690 --> 00:43:00.990
much for coming in to Google.

00:43:00.990 --> 00:43:03.230
We really appreciate
you coming here.

00:43:03.230 --> 00:43:06.110
For everyone else, the
book is available outside--

00:43:06.110 --> 00:43:07.501
"Mustache Shenanigans."

00:43:07.501 --> 00:43:09.500
And he'll be sticking
around to take some photos

00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:10.280
and some autographs.

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:10.920
Thanks again, Jay.

00:43:10.920 --> 00:43:11.220
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR: Thanks.

00:43:11.220 --> 00:43:11.520
ALLAN WEINBERGER:
Appreciate the time.

00:43:11.520 --> 00:43:12.895
JAY CHANDRASEKHAR:
Appreciate it.

